1. Install the waybar service
Copy waybar.service to the systemd user services directory. Create it first if it doesn't exist:
mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user/
cp waybar.service ~/.config/systemd/user/

2. Enable and start the service
Tell systemd to start waybar now and automatically on every login:
bashsystemctl --user enable --now waybar.service

3. Hand waybar over to systemd
From now on systemd will manage waybar, so you need to remove any lines that launch waybar directly from your compositor config (e.g. exec waybar or exec-once = waybar), otherwise it will start twice.
Then add the following so your compositor signals systemd when it's ready, which is what triggers waybar to start at the right time:

Sway (~/.config/sway/config):

exec systemctl --user start waybar.service


Hyprland (~/.config/hypr/hyprland.conf):

exec systemctl --user start waybar.service


Using a mainstream display manager? (SDDM, GDM, LightDM, etc.) — your login manager likely activates graphical-session.target automatically, so you may not need to add those lines at all. 
In that case, just make sure waybar.service has After=graphical-session.target and WantedBy=graphical-session.target dependencies instead of the above.
